{
  "doc_id": "39353",
  "text": "However, more recent empirical studies in the boom-bust literature, including [CITATION_1] and [CITATION_2] , tell another story. As capital flows to a country, it triggers a domestic credit boom. A channel for this is that capital inflows will eventually have to be exchanged or converted to domestic currency. This technically leads to an expansion of money supply, which puts downward pressure on domestic interest rates. But lower interest rate will reduce the cost of borrowing, which will increase investment and output. In this case, capital inflows are expansionary. Empirical evidence including those from [CITATION_3] , as well as policy dilemma faced by emerging economies indicate that capital inflows lead to currency appreciations, credit booms, and output increases. This could potentially lead to contractions, crises, and reversals of capital inflows. In short, theory and empirics point to an amalgamation of capital flows effects.",
